This comes as bad news for President Cyril Ramaphosa, who won last month's election after pledging to transform the struggling economy and attract investment. The poor economic results were largely due to contractions in the agriculture and mining sectors. South Africa's Central Bank had predicted economic growth of around 1% this year, but financial analysts now say there is a risk that Africa's most industrialised economy could go into recession for the second time in as many years.  --Reuters-- 